<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Jerycho on 05-27-2002 10:49 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">My ideas - for which I'm sure to be hated by all  :)

1) Nerf complete heal to a 4k limit. That's still an awesome mana ratio. No spell should provide anyone essentially unlimited power in one area. 4k heal would be awesome. The only reason anyone will be against this is that we are so used to healing for 5-7k now. But pre-luclin, and certainly pre-vellious, no tank had more than 4k.

2) Give the nerfed complete heal to druids and shaman, further nerfing it to cost 800 mana and have a recast time about half again as long as ours. This makes them usefull backup healers for when we are oom. Face it, right now the complaint is that they are SUPPOSSED to be back up healers but they can't do it. And they're right. This would allow them to do it, but at a very high price.

3) Address our ability to buff offense. We should have some form of prayer spell that raises atk by a fair margin. This should be long lasting, fairly high level and cost a mint in terms of mana. Let it stack with damn near everything.

4) We need an aa ability to drop DL down to about 2 seconds cast with zero refresh.

5) seriously consider removing "unlsowable" and "unsnarable" (hell as well as "unmezzable") from the game entirely. Instead recode so that those types of spells have a "counter" for each person casting the spell. normal mobs would only need 1 counter to land for effect. Maybe kunark giants would need 3 counters to land for the effect to work. Dragons might need 5 or 6. High end uber mobs might need 10 or more. This would make shaman and druids MUCH more stackable -and even necessary - on some raids. It would also open up the tactics bag to different tricks.

Instead of 10 clerics for the AoW you could have 10 shaman and 10 druids but only 3 clerics. The shaman are needed to slow him, hte druids needed to snare him, and now the 3 clerics are sufficient...
</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
